  • 0.1 We expect the sample mean to be close to population and the standev to get smaller by the ratio of one to the sample size. In this case 1/sqrt(2)
    • 0.1.1 There are 3 peaks in the density plot. You pick two people you can get MM,MF.FM,or FF. these are all equally likey so the little peak on left is all the FFs while the little peak on the right is all the MMs so the big one in the middle is both the MF and FM in the same bag so-to-speak.
    • 0.1.2 In this case the stdev was cut in half because the sample size was four. This is what the central limit theorem says. There are also 5 peaks. They go from FFFF,to FFFM, to FFMM to FMMM and finally MMMM.

Homers_data <- read.csv(file="Homers_data.csv")

my1000 <- sample(Homers_data , size = 1000, replace=T)
library(ggplot2)
sampleNumber = sample(1:10000, size = 1000)
library(dplyr)
my1000 <- Homers_data[sampleNumber, ]
names(my1000)
## [1] "sex"          "math"         "income"       "cappun"       "height"      
## [6] "idealheight"  "diff"         "kkardashtemp"
# Basic density
p <- ggplot(my1000, aes(x=kkardashtemp,col=sex)) + 
  geom_density()
p

# Add mean line
p+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(kkardashtemp)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)

0.1 We expect the sample mean to be close to population and the standev to get smaller by the ratio of one to the sample size. In this case 1/sqrt(2)

0.1.1 There are 3 peaks in the density plot. You pick two people you can get MM,MF.FM,or FF. these are all equally likey so the little peak on left is all the FFs while the little peak on the right is all the MMs so the big one in the middle is both the MF and FM in the same bag so-to-speak.

numb = 4
Hdata = Homers_data[sample(1:1000,size=numb*1000, replace=T),"kkardashtemp"]
mdata  <-matrix(Hdata,nrow=1000,ncol=numb)
x.avg <- apply(mdata,1,mean)
my1000$k4 = x.avg


p <- ggplot(my1000, aes(x=k4),col=sex) + 
  geom_density() +

# Add mean line
 geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(k4)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)
p + ggtitle("n = 4") +
  xlab("temperature") + ylab(" density")

0.1.2 In this case the stdev was cut in half because the sample size was four. This is what the central limit theorem says. There are also 5 peaks. They go from FFFF,to FFFM, to FFMM to FMMM and finally MMMM.
